# Trivy CVE exemptions — narrow, per-CVE, with written reason + upgrade plan.
# Each entry MUST include the CVE id, the affected package path, the reason
# the exemption is safe today, and the trigger that retires the exemption.
#
# Adding entries here is a structural escape hatch for the Trivy gate. Use
# sparingly: prefer fixing the dep over ignoring it.

# ── npm CLI transitive deps (node:22-alpine base image) ──
#
# The next four entries all flag CVEs in dependencies of the npm CLI
# that ships with the node:22-alpine base image, not in our app's
# node_modules tree. The shared reachability argument:
#
#   - The vulnerable packages live in
#     `usr/local/lib/node_modules/npm/node_modules/...`, i.e. they
#     are loaded only when the `npm` binary itself is invoked.
#   - `npm install` runs at build time (Docker `RUN npm install`) on
#     our own package.json. No untrusted input flows in.
#   - The runtime container never execs `npm` — the final image's
#     CMD is the Next.js server. Application code does not
#     `child_process.spawn('npm', ...)` anywhere.
#   - App-level reachability is therefore zero.
#
# Each entry is retired when the Node base image bundles an npm CLI
# whose transitive lockfile no longer carries the vulnerable version.
# A single base-image bump usually retires several exemptions at once.

# CVE-2026-33671 — picomatch < 4.0.4 RegEx DoS
#   Affected path:  usr/local/lib/node_modules/npm/node_modules/picomatch (v4.0.3)
#   Why exempt:     The picomatch instance flagged here is bundled INSIDE
#                   the npm CLI that ships with the node:22-alpine base
#                   image — it's not in our application's dependency tree
#                   (our app's picomatch is pinned to ^4.0.4 via the
#                   `overrides` block in package.json).
#   Upgrade plan:   Resolved when the Node base image ships an npm CLI
#                   that pins picomatch >= 4.0.4 (or 3.0.2 / 2.3.2). The
#                   next Node image refresh PR removes this entry.
CVE-2026-33671

# CVE-2026-33672 — picomatch method injection via POSIX bracket expressions
#   Affected path:  usr/local/lib/node_modules/npm/node_modules/picomatch
#   Why exempt:     Same reasoning as CVE-2026-33671 — the vulnerable
#                   picomatch is inside the npm CLI, not in our app
#                   tree. Our app's picomatch is `^4.0.4` via the
#                   overrides block. POSIX bracket expressions are not
#                   user-supplied at build time (the package.json file
#                   patterns are written by the team, not derived from
#                   untrusted input).
#   Upgrade plan:   Cleared by the same base-image bump as
#                   CVE-2026-33671 — both target the same picomatch
#                   install path.
CVE-2026-33672

# CVE-2026-33750 — brace-expansion DoS via zero-step brace patterns
#   Affected path:  usr/local/lib/node_modules/npm/node_modules/brace-expansion
#   Why exempt:     brace-expansion is loaded by glob / minimatch
#                   patterns inside the npm CLI's package resolution
#                   logic. The only patterns it processes at build
#                   time are the `files` glob in our own package.json
#                   and the `.npmignore` / `.gitignore` patterns —
#                   all of which are committed source-controlled
#                   content, not untrusted input. A zero-step brace
#                   pattern in our source code is something we'd
#                   notice in code review, not something a remote
#                   attacker can inject.
#   Upgrade plan:   Cleared by the next base-image bump that ships
#                   an npm CLI with brace-expansion >= the fixed
#                   version range.
CVE-2026-33750

# CVE-2026-42338 — ip-address XSS in Address6 HTML-emitting methods
#   Affected path:  usr/local/lib/node_modules/npm/node_modules/ip-address
#   Why exempt:     `ip-address` is loaded inside the npm CLI for
#                   parsing registry URLs (npm validates the host
#                   field of `registry` entries in `.npmrc` and
#                   resolves IPv6-shaped hosts via this lib). The
#                   XSS sinks are the Address6 HTML-render methods,
#                   which the CLI never calls (it parses, it doesn't
#                   render HTML). Even if the methods WERE invoked,
#                   they'd render into the build host's stderr, not
#                   into the running container's user-facing surface.
#   Upgrade plan:   Cleared by the next base-image bump that ships
#                   an npm CLI with the patched `ip-address` version.
CVE-2026-42338
